Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_550
Response Text: I strongly feel that the City has lost interest in supporting more "traditional" arts groups, regardless of their proven track records for attracting audiences and being good stewards of the grant money they are awarded. I was on the board of Ensemble VIII (Renaissance/Baroque choral music) from its inception in 2011 until it was forced out of existence in 2024 due to lack of public funding. Private funding sources were steady/increased during that time. State/national funding continued, but was much less than what the City had provided for the first many years. When the criteria changed for City of Austin grants to focus almost entirely on new organizations and "diversity," Ensemble VIII lost all funding from the City, even though our audience size never waned (except during Covid, of course). The organization was highly critically acclaimed and much loved by longtime audience members. I'm sure there are other organizations that suffered the same fate due to decisions made by the City about where arts funding should be focused. I hope this will change so that there is also a diversity of genres supported, including longtime arts organizations in Austin that still need, and deserve, public financial support.

